fn.p:
1.Analyzed duration for lunging and tussling (Figure 2G), supporting that tussling is a much more intensive fighting form than lunging.
2.Provided higher-resolution images of P1a and pC1SS2 for clarity (Figure 4C-4E);
3.Performed co-staining experiments and found that P1a neurons are partially FruM-positive and partially DsxM-positive, while pC1SS2 neurons are DsxM-positive and FruM-negative (Figure 5A-5D);
4.Knocking down DsxM expression in pC1SS2 neurons using RNAi significantly affected their development regarding to both cell numbers (Figure 5E-5G) and their projections (Figure 5H); as well as their tussling-promoting function (Figure 5I-5K);
5.Utilizing trans-Tango and retro-Tango to visualize potential downstream and upstream neurons of P1a and pC1SS2 (Figure 4-figure supplement 2);
6.Analyzed tussling behavior between a SH male and a GH male and found that they displayed similar levels of tussling like two GH males, although tussling duration from paired SH and GH males is significantly lower compared to that in two GH males (Figure 6-figure supplement 2).
7.Performed additional experiments and found that males with Or47b or pC1SS2 neurons silenced cannot compete over control males (Figure 6-figure supplement 3), further suggesting the involvement of tussling in territory control and mating competition.
